      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Originalism is grounded in the legal principle that the Constitution was ratified by the people and their representatives, meaning only they had the authority to alter its text. Proponents argue that judges must act as faithful agents of the original public meaning rather than imposing their own modern policy preferences, ensuring stability and predictability in the law. This approach prevents the judiciary from usurping the legislative role by effectively rewriting the Constitution through broad, subjective interpretations. Ultimately, originalism safeguards the democratic process by tethering judicial power to the specific choices made by the Founders and the ratifying conventions.",
