      "content": "You are absolutely right to be skeptical, because critics often use this exact argument to attack the legitimacy of the method. However, originalists counter that this skepticism is actually the strongest argument *for* the method, not against it, because it forces us to confront the fact that *any* interpretation is inherently political. By demanding a specific historical anchor, originalism strips away the \"magic\" of judicial discretion and forces judges to justify their rulings based on the actual choices of the Founders rather than their own personal ideology. If we accept that all law is political, then originalism is simply the most honest framework because it admits that the Constitution is a historical document, not a living policy manual.",
